out 1045":"circa 1045","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England":"Kirklington, Yorkshire, England","Normandy or Brittanny":"Normandie, Frankrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1045–after 1085":"about 1045–after 1085","1045–1085":"1045–1085","–1069":"–1069","–Female":"Deceased","1080–Male":"1080–Deceased","–1131":"–1131","1025–Male":"1025–Deceased","1080":"1080","1025":"1025","1069":"1069","about 1080":"about 1080","before 1045":"before 1045","1045":"1045","after 1085":"after 1085","1066":"1066","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","about 1045":"about 1045","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England":"Kirklington, Yorkshire, England","Normandy or Brittanny":"Normandy, France","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Musters","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: locative name from Les Moutiers-Hubert (Calvados)."],"variants":[{"name":"Muster","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Hans, Bernhard, Heinz.","German: occupational name for a producer or seller of ‘most’, unfermented grape juice, fruit wine, from Middle Low German <i>must, most</i>, Middle High German <i>most</i> (see   Most  ).","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Mostar</b> (see   Moster  ), a cognate of 4 below."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":21,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":41,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Musters was born about 1045, in Normandy, France as the son of Lisois de Monsaterlis and Mrs. Lisois de Monasteriis. He had at least 2 sons with Muriel. He died after 1085, in Kirklington, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1045–after 1085":"umbes 1045–pärast 1085","1045–1085":"1045–1085","–1069":"–1069","–Female":"Surnud","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","–1131":"–1131","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1080":"1080","1025":"1025","1069":"1069","about 1080":"umbes 1080","before 1045":"enne 1045","1045":"1045","after 1085":"pärast 1085","1066":"1066","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","about 1045":"umbes 1045","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England":"Kirklington, Yorkshire, England","Normandy or Brittanny":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1045–after 1085":"noin 1045–1085 jälkeen","1045–1085":"1045–1085","–1069":"–1069","–Female":"Kuollut","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","–1131":"–1131","1025–Male":"1025–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1025":"1025","1069":"1069","about 1080":"noin 1080","before 1045":"ennen vuotta 1045","1045":"1045","after 1085":"1085 jälkeen","1066":"1066","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","about 1045":"noin 1045","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England":"Kirklington, Yorkshire, England","Normandy or Brittanny":"Normandie, Ranska","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1045–after 1085":"environ 1045–après 1085","1045–1085":"1045–1085","–1069":"–1069","–Female":"Décédée","1080–Male":"1080–Décédé","–1131":"–1131","1025–Male":"1025–Décédé","1080":"1080","1025":"1025","1069":"1069","about 1080":"environ 1080","before 1045":"avant 1045","1045":"1045","after 1085":"après 1085","1066":"1066","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","about 1045":"environ 1045","Kirklington, Yorkshire, England":"Kirklington, Everwyck, Angleterre","Normandy or Brittanny":"Normandie, France","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Musters est né environ 1045, à Normandie, France, fils de Lisois de Monsaterlis et Mrs. L